    <div class="container">
        <section id="how-it-works">
            <h2>How HTML Works</h2>
            <p>HTML, or HyperText Markup Language, is the standard language used to create web pages. It uses tags to structure content like headings, paragraphs, images, and links. Browsers interpret these tags to display content visually.</p>
            <pre><code>&lt;h1&gt;This is a Heading&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="history">
            <h2>History of HTML</h2>
            <p>HTML was invented by Tim Berners-Lee in 1991 as part of his vision for the World Wide Web. The language has evolved over time, with major versions like HTML4 in 1997 and HTML5 in 2014, adding new features to meet the web's growing needs.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="advantages-disadvantages">
            <h2>Advantages and Disadvantages</h2>
            <h3>Advantages:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Simple and easy to learn</li>
                <li>Widely supported by all web browsers</li>
                <li>Forms the foundation of web development</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Disadvantages:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Static and lacks dynamic behavior without additional technologies</li>
                <li>Can become complex for large projects</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="fun-facts">
            <h2>Fun Facts About HTML</h2>
            <div class="funfact">
                <p>Did you know? The first website created by Tim Berners-Lee is still online at <a href="http://info.cern.ch" target="_blank">info.cern.ch</a>.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="funfact">
                <p>HTML5 introduced new elements like <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;section&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, which make structuring websites easier.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
